    'pe.intro.label': 'Introduction',
    'pe.intro.title': 'What is private equity?',
    'pe.intro.p': 'Private equity means investing money directly into companies that are not listed on a stock exchange. Investors buy a stake in a business, work to make it more valuable over a number of years, and then sell that stake, ideally at a profit. The money comes from a private equity fund, which pools capital from large investors such as pension funds, insurers and wealthy individuals.',
    'pe.what.h': 'How it works in short',
    'pe.what1.t': 'What it is',
    'pe.what1.d': 'Investing in private companies, or buying a listed company and taking it private, with the aim of growing its value and selling later.',
    'pe.what2.t': 'How funds make money',
    'pe.what2.d': 'By improving how a company performs and buying and selling at the right price. Firms often use debt to finance a purchase, which can raise the return on their own capital.',
    'pe.what3.t': 'Why companies sell',
    'pe.what3.d': 'A founder retires, a family cashes out, a group sells a division, or a business needs capital and expertise to grow. Private equity offers money and hands-on support in exchange for ownership.',
    'pe.what4.t': 'Why students like it',
    'pe.what4.d': 'It combines finance, strategy and real ownership of business decisions. The work is analytical and varied, responsibility comes early, and the pay is among the highest in finance.',
