    'cf.faq.0.q': 'What is corporate finance?',
    'cf.faq.0.a': 'As a career, corporate finance is the finance function inside a company. The team manages the company’s own funding, investments, planning, cash and risk from the inside, and reports up to the chief financial officer.',
    'cf.faq.1.q': 'Is corporate finance the same as investment banking?',
    'cf.faq.1.a': 'Not as a career. Corporate finance works in-house for one company, while investment banking and M&A advise many companies on deals from the outside for a fee. Confusingly, at the Big Four and boutiques the M&A advisory team is often called corporate finance.',
    'cf.faq.2.q': 'What does a corporate finance department do?',
    'cf.faq.2.a': 'It plans and budgets, decides how the company is funded, assesses investments, manages cash and risk through treasury, runs in-house acquisitions through corporate development, and reports results to management.',
    'cf.faq.3.q': 'What is FP&A?',
    'cf.faq.3.a': 'FP&A stands for financial planning and analysis. It is the team that builds budgets and forecasts, analyses why results differ from plan, and provides the numbers behind management decisions.',
    'cf.faq.4.q': 'Do you need a certification like RC or CFA?',
    'cf.faq.4.a': 'Not to start. A bachelor’s degree is enough for most entry-level roles. Later, a Dutch Register Controller (RC) qualification is well regarded for controlling, and CMA, ACCA or CFA can help depending on the role.',
    'cf.faq.5.q': 'How many hours do you work in corporate finance?',
    'cf.faq.5.a': 'Usually around forty to fifty hours a week, busier around month-end, quarter-end and budget season. It is generally more predictable than advisory or banking roles.',
    'cf.faq.6.q': 'What skills do I need?',
    'cf.faq.6.a': 'A solid grasp of accounting, financial modelling and forecasting, strong Excel, business sense, comfort with data and reporting systems, attention to detail and clear communication.',
    'cf.faq.7.q': 'How do I get into corporate finance?',
    'cf.faq.7.a': 'Apply for finance graduate programmes and internships at large companies, or move in after a few years in audit. Recruit at target universities, build modelling and accounting skills, and network with people in finance teams.',
