    'ib.faq.0.q': 'What is investment banking?',
    'ib.faq.0.a': 'Investment banking helps companies, institutions and governments raise money and carry out major deals, such as share issues, bond issues and mergers. The bank acts as an adviser and intermediary, not as a place to hold deposits.',
    'ib.faq.1.q': 'How do investment banks make money?',
    'ib.faq.1.a': 'Mainly through fees: for advising on deals such as mergers, and for arranging capital raises like IPOs and bond issues.',
    'ib.faq.2.q': 'What does an analyst do?',
    'ib.faq.2.a': 'Analysts build financial models, do research, prepare pitchbooks and support senior bankers on live deals. It is analytical, detail-heavy work with long hours.',
    'ib.faq.3.q': 'How many hours do investment bankers work?',
    'ib.faq.3.a': 'Junior bankers often work seventy to eighty hours a week, with late nights and weekends during live deals. Hours usually improve at more senior levels.',
    'ib.faq.4.q': 'Do you need an MBA?',
    'ib.faq.4.a': 'Not to start as an analyst, which is usually filled straight from university. An MBA is the classic route into the associate level and can speed up progression.',
    'ib.faq.5.q': 'What is the difference between investment banking and private equity?',
    'ib.faq.5.a': 'Banking advises clients on deals and raising capital and earns fees. Private equity invests its own fund, buys companies and earns from improving and selling them.',
    'ib.faq.6.q': 'What skills do I need?',
    'ib.faq.6.a': 'Strong analytical thinking, financial modelling and valuation, a solid grasp of accounting, attention to detail, clear communication and the ability to work under pressure.',
    'ib.faq.7.q': 'How do I get an internship?',
    'ib.faq.7.a': 'Apply early through spring weeks and summer internship programmes, recruit at target universities, network with bankers and alumni, and prepare hard for technical interviews.',
    'vc.diff.p3': 'In the Netherlands and the rest of Europe, funds are usually smaller than the large American ones, but the ecosystem, especially around Amsterdam, has grown strongly. Most Dutch venture capital goes into early and growth-stage companies in technology, health and sustainability.',
    'vc.diff.p4': 'Valuing an early-stage company is not the same exercise as valuing a listed business. There is no earnings history to build a discounted cash flow model on, so investors and founders typically negotiate a valuation based on comparable recent rounds, the size of the market and how much dilution the founders are willing to accept. Each new round issues new shares, so every investor\'s ownership percentage shrinks unless they use their right to invest again, known as a pro rata right, to keep their stake roughly stable.',
    'vc.dia.bcaption': 'The path a startup follows, from its first funding to an exit through a sale or an IPO.',
