    'vc.vs.0.t': 'Venture capital vs private equity',
    'vc.vs.0.d': 'Venture capital backs young, risky startups with minority stakes. Private equity buys mature, profitable companies, often in full and with debt. That debt, used in a leveraged buyout, is repaid using the target company\'s own cash flow, which only works if the business generates stable, predictable earnings, something an early-stage startup rarely has. Private equity funds also typically take board control and can replace management, while venture investors usually hold one board seat alongside the founders who stay in charge.',
    'vc.vs.1.t': 'Venture capital vs growth equity',
    'vc.vs.1.d': 'Growth equity invests in companies that already grow and earn money, with less risk. Venture capital comes in earlier, when much is still unproven. Growth investors typically buy a minority stake without board control and rarely use debt, closer in structure to venture capital than to a buyout, but the underwriting question is different: instead of betting on whether a market and product will work at all, they are betting on whether a working business can keep growing at a similar pace.',
    'vc.vs.2.t': 'Venture capital vs angel investing',
    'vc.vs.2.d': 'Angels invest their own money in very early companies. Venture funds invest other people\'s money, in larger amounts and with a formal process.',
    'vc.vs.3.t': 'Venture capital vs corporate VC',
    'vc.vs.3.d': 'Corporate venture funds invest on behalf of a large company, often for strategic reasons. Independent funds invest purely for financial return.',
    'vc.vs.4.t': 'Venture capital vs investment banking',
    'vc.vs.4.d': 'Banking advises companies on deals and raising money. Venture capital invests its own fund and works with founders over many years.',
