    'pe.faq.0.q': 'What is private equity?',
    'pe.faq.0.a': 'Private equity is investing directly in companies that are not listed on a stock exchange. Investors buy a stake, work to grow the company value over several years and then sell it.',
    'pe.faq.1.q': 'How do private equity firms make money?',
    'pe.faq.1.a': 'They earn from improving and reselling companies at a higher value, often using debt to raise returns. The firm also charges a management fee and keeps a share of the profit.',
    'pe.faq.2.q': 'Is private equity harder to enter than investment banking?',
    'pe.faq.2.a': 'Usually yes. Firms are smaller and hire fewer people, and many roles expect prior experience, often from investment banking or consulting.',
    'pe.faq.3.q': 'Can students apply directly to private equity?',
    'pe.faq.3.a': 'Some firms offer internships and working student roles, especially smaller and mid-market funds. Many analyst roles are filled by people who first worked in banking or consulting.',
    'pe.faq.4.q': 'Do you need investment banking first?',
    'pe.faq.4.a': 'Not always, but it is the most common route. Banking teaches modelling, valuation and deal work. Consulting, transaction services and corporate finance are other routes.',
    'pe.faq.5.q': 'What is an LBO?',
    'pe.faq.5.a': 'A leveraged buyout is buying a company using a large amount of borrowed money. The debt is repaid from the company cash flow, which can increase the return on the investor own capital.',
    'pe.faq.6.q': 'What skills should I learn first?',
    'pe.faq.6.a': 'Start with accounting and valuation, then financial modelling in Excel. Add clear writing and commercial thinking. These are the foundations for almost every task.',
    'pe.faq.7.q': 'Which internships help most?',
    'pe.faq.7.a': 'Internships in investment banking, transaction services, corporate finance, valuation or a smaller private equity fund are the most useful.',
