    'com.skills.label': 'Skills',
    'com.skills.text': 'Legal knowledge gets the most attention in training, but the lawyers who stay longest often stand out through commercial judgement: understanding what the client is really trying to achieve with a contract, not just what it literally says.',
    'com.skills.title': 'Skills you will need',
    'com.sub': 'Discover what commercial (contract law) means in legal practice: how lawyers draft the contracts that let businesses do business with each other, what they do day to day, the career ladder, and how students prepare for an internship or traineeship.',
    'com.tier.0.d': 'Firms that handle cross-border trade contracts and international distribution networks.',
    'com.tier.0.t': 'International firm',
    'com.tier.1.d': 'A commercial practice alongside other practice groups, often close to IP or corporate.',
    'com.tier.1.t': 'Dutch full-service firm',
    'com.tier.2.d': 'Company lawyers who review and draft the organisation\'s own purchase, sale and cooperation contracts.',
    'com.tier.2.t': 'In-house at a company',
    'com.tier.label': 'The practice',
    'com.tier.text': 'The breakdown below mainly says something about the client you serve, not about the quality of the work. The same contract question can come up at an international firm, a Dutch full-service firm, or in-house at a company, each with a slightly different angle.',
    'com.tier.text2': 'At international firms you often work on cross-border supply and distribution agreements with parties in multiple countries. At Dutch full-service firms, the commercial practice often sits directly alongside the intellectual property or corporate team. In-house at a company, you review contracts from the perspective of your own organisation, with a lot of repetition and volume.',
    'com.tier.title': 'Three settings where you practise this field',
    'com.tl.label': 'Career timeline',
    'com.tl.p1': 'The legal profession has a fixed statutory basis for the first step: a traineeship in the Netherlands generally lasts three years and is mandatory for every starting lawyer, regardless of practice area. After that, the pace of progression depends heavily on the firm and on individual performance.',
    'com.tl.p2': 'After the traineeship, the emphasis shifts from drafting contracts to independently leading matters. Making partner takes more than ten years of legal experience at most firms, and is often accompanied by a formal nomination by the existing partners.',
    'com.tl.p3': 'Not everyone climbs the whole ladder at the same firm. Some lawyers move to a company after a few years, for example as in-house counsel, bringing their legal-practice experience with them.',
    'com.tl.th1': 'Level',
    'com.tl.th2': 'Typical time in role',
    'com.tl.title': 'How long each step takes',
    'com.tl.y1': '3 years, mandatory by law',
    'com.tl.y2': '3 to 5 years',
    'com.tl.y3': '2 to 4 years',
    'com.tl.y4': 'top level, 10+ years in total',
