    'cma.w2.t': 'What it centres on',
    'cma.w3.d': 'To complete an acquisition, merger or restructuring in a legally sound, risk-aware way.',
    'cma.w3.t': 'Why clients need it',
    'cma.w4.d': 'Visible deal moments, international transactions, and a direct view of the entire acquisition process.',
    'cma.w4.t': 'Why students find it attractive',

    'dr.badge': 'Legal career path',
    'dr.h1': 'Dispute Resolution',
    'dr.sub': 'Discover what dispute resolution means in legal practice: how lawyers conduct proceedings before courts and arbitrators, what they do day to day, the career ladder, and how students prepare for an internship or traineeship.',
    'dr.cta.vac': 'View vacancies',
    'dr.cta.paths': 'Explore legal paths',
    'dr.intro.label': 'Introduction',
    'dr.intro.title': 'What is dispute resolution?',
    'dr.intro.p': 'Dispute resolution, often called litigation or procedural law in the Netherlands, is the practice area centred on resolving legal conflicts: through the courts, through arbitration, or through mediation. Where most other practice areas aim to prevent disputes, dispute resolution steps in precisely when parties can no longer agree.',
    'dr.intro.p2': 'A proceeding starts with a writ of summons or a petition and then follows a fixed procedural path: exchanging submissions, presenting evidence, an oral hearing, and eventually a judgment. In arbitration and mediation, the process is less fixed and parties have more influence over its form.',
    'dr.intro.p3': 'Dispute resolution lawyers often work with the practice group the underlying dispute comes from: a contract dispute touches commercial, a shareholder dispute touches corporate/M&A, and a dispute with the government touches administrative law.',
    'dr.w1.t': 'What it is',
    'dr.w1.d': 'The practice area covering the resolution of legal conflicts, through the courts, arbitration or mediation.',
    'dr.w2.t': 'What it centres on',
    'dr.w2.d': 'Building a case file, conducting proceedings, and tracking procedural deadlines.',
    'dr.w3.t': 'Why clients need it',
    'dr.w3.d': 'To resolve a dispute with a counterparty effectively and with a good outcome.',
    'dr.w4.t': 'Why students find it attractive',
    'dr.w4.d': 'Visible hearing moments, sharp legal argumentation, and direct contact with the court.',
    'dr.tier.label': 'The practice',
    'dr.tier.title': 'Three settings where you practise this field',
    'dr.tier.text': 'The breakdown below mainly says something about the type of dispute and the client you serve, not about the quality of the work.',
    'dr.tier.0.t': 'International firm',
    'dr.tier.0.d': 'Firms that handle large, often cross-border commercial disputes and international arbitrations.',
    'dr.tier.1.t': 'Dutch full-service firm',
    'dr.tier.1.d': 'A litigation practice alongside other practice groups, often brought in once a matter escalates.',
    'dr.tier.2.t': 'Legal expense insurer or regional firm',
    'dr.tier.2.d': 'Handles a high volume of smaller, often consumer-facing disputes.',
    'dr.tier.text2': 'At international firms you work on large, often cross-border disputes and international arbitrations. At Dutch full-service firms, the litigation practice often sits close to the practice group the underlying dispute comes from. At a legal expense insurer or regional firm, you handle a larger volume of smaller disputes, often on behalf of individuals or SMEs.',
    'dr.do.label': 'What they do',
    'dr.do.title': 'What dispute resolution lawyers do',
    'dr.do.text': 'The work differs by proceeding, but the building blocks below come up in almost every dispute. A lawyer often works on several proceedings at once, each with its own deadlines.',
    'dr.do.0.t': 'Building the case file',
    'dr.do.0.d': 'Structuring facts, evidence and legal arguments for a proceeding.',
    'dr.do.1.t': 'Drafting the writ of summons or petition',
    'dr.do.1.d': 'Drafting the submission that formally starts a proceeding.',
    'dr.do.2.t': 'Pleading before the court',
    'dr.do.2.d': 'Presenting the client\'s position orally during a hearing.',
    'dr.do.3.t': 'Coordinating evidence',
    'dr.do.3.d': 'Using witnesses, experts and documents to substantiate a claim.',
    'dr.do.4.t': 'Conducting settlement negotiations',
    'dr.do.4.d': 'Assessing whether an amicable solution is preferable to continued litigation.',
    'dr.do.5.t': 'Guiding arbitration proceedings',
    'dr.do.5.d': 'Having disputes resolved by arbitrators instead of the state court.',
    'dr.do.6.t': 'Preparing summary proceedings',
    'dr.do.6.d': 'Setting up an urgent proceeding when a ruling cannot wait.',
    'dr.do.7.t': 'Coordinating with other practice groups',
    'dr.do.7.d': 'Working with the practice group the underlying dispute stems from.',
    'dr.law.label': 'Legal framework',
    'dr.law.title': 'The key legislation',
    'dr.law.text': 'Dispute resolution revolves around a limited set of core rules from procedural law that keep recurring, even though the substance differs greatly from case to case.',
    'dr.law.0.t': 'Dutch Code of Civil Procedure',
    'dr.law.0.d': 'Governs civil procedural law: how a proceeding is started and conducted.',
    'dr.law.1.t': 'Books 3 and 6 of the Dutch Civil Code',
    'dr.law.1.d': 'The substantive rules on obligations that a claim is often based on.',
    'dr.law.2.t': 'Arbitration Act (Book 4 of the Code of Civil Procedure)',
    'dr.law.2.d': 'Governs arbitration proceedings as an alternative to the state court.',
    'dr.law.3.t': 'Mediation Act',
    'dr.law.3.d': 'Governs the quality safeguards around mediation as a form of dispute resolution.',
    'dr.law.4.t': 'Brussels I bis Regulation',
    'dr.law.4.d': 'EU rules on jurisdiction and recognition of judgments in cross-border disputes.',
    'dr.law.5.t': 'Act on the Settlement of Mass Damages in Collective Actions (WAMCA)',
    'dr.law.5.d': 'Governs collective damages claims on behalf of large groups of affected parties.',
    'dr.div.label': 'Practice areas',
    'dr.div.title': 'The main sub-areas',
    'dr.div.text': 'Dispute resolution is broad, and most lawyers specialise within one of the sub-areas below.',
    'dr.div.0.t': 'Civil proceedings',
    'dr.div.0.d': 'Disputes between businesses or individuals before the civil court.',
    'dr.div.1.t': 'Arbitration',
    'dr.div.1.d': 'Dispute resolution by an arbitrator instead of the state court, often in international contracts.',
    'dr.div.2.t': 'Mediation',
    'dr.div.2.d': 'Guided negotiation aimed at a solution without a court proceeding.',
    'dr.div.3.t': 'Summary proceedings',
    'dr.div.3.d': 'Urgent proceedings where a provisional ruling is needed quickly.',
    'dr.div.4.t': 'Collective actions',
    'dr.div.4.d': 'Mass claims on behalf of large groups of affected parties, often against large companies.',
    'dr.dp.label': 'Step by step',
    'dr.dp.title': 'How a civil proceeding unfolds',
    'dr.dp.text': 'Most civil proceedings follow a similar path, from the writ of summons to the judgment. In more complex cases, presenting evidence can take considerable time.',
    'dr.dp.text2': 'Who does which step depends on seniority. Junior lawyers build the case file and work out submissions in detail, while senior lawyers plead and discuss procedural risks with the client.',
    'dr.dp.text3': 'Not every proceeding ends in a judgment: parties can still settle at any point, which is often faster and cheaper than litigating all the way through a possible appeal.',
    'dr.dp.0': 'Writ of summons',
    'dr.dp.1': 'Statement of defence',
    'dr.dp.2': 'Evidence',
    'dr.dp.3': 'Oral hearing',
    'dr.dp.4': 'Judgment',
    'dr.dp.5': 'Appeal',
    'dr.dp.caption': 'A simplified overview of a civil proceeding: the writ of summons, the counterparty\'s statement of defence, presenting evidence, the oral hearing, the judgment, and any appeal.',
    'dr.roles.label': 'Roles',
    'dr.roles.title': 'Roles in the dispute resolution practice',
    'dr.roles.text': 'Each step up the ladder shifts the emphasis further from building the case file toward setting litigation strategy and pleading before the court. Most lawyers climb this ladder at the same firm, though moving between firms at any level is common.',
    'dr.role.tasks': 'Key tasks',
