    'dr.faq.label': 'FAQ',
    'dr.faq.title': 'Frequently asked questions',
    'dr.faq.0.q': 'What is dispute resolution?',
    'dr.faq.0.a': 'Dispute resolution, often called litigation or procedural law in the Netherlands, is the practice area centred on resolving legal conflicts through the courts, arbitration or mediation.',
    'dr.faq.1.q': 'What is the difference between arbitration and court proceedings?',
    'dr.faq.1.a': 'In court proceedings, the state court resolves the dispute under the Code of Civil Procedure. In arbitration, parties choose one or more arbitrators to resolve the dispute themselves, often faster and more confidentially, based on an arbitration clause in their contract.',
    'dr.faq.2.q': 'What does a dispute resolution lawyer do day to day?',
    'dr.faq.2.a': 'Dispute resolution lawyers build case files, draft submissions, plead before the court, conduct settlement negotiations, and guide clients through arbitration or mediation proceedings.',
    'dr.faq.3.q': 'What are summary proceedings?',
    'dr.faq.3.a': 'Summary proceedings are an urgent procedure in which the court quickly issues a provisional ruling, for example to prevent an imminent violation of rights. A definitive ruling may follow later in a proceedings on the merits.',
    'dr.faq.4.q': 'What is mediation and when is it used?',
    'dr.faq.4.a': 'Mediation is a guided negotiation between parties led by an independent mediator, aimed at a solution without a court proceeding. It is often used when parties want to preserve an ongoing relationship.',
    'dr.faq.5.q': 'What is a collective action (WAMCA)?',
    'dr.faq.5.a': 'A collective action is a proceeding in which an interest organisation files a claim on behalf of a large group of affected parties, for example against a company. The WAMCA sets out the conditions under which such a collective damages claim is possible.',
    'dr.faq.6.q': 'What skills do you need for dispute resolution?',
    'dr.faq.6.a': 'Precise writing, persuasiveness, strong oral presentation, attention to detail, and the ability to work under the pressure of procedural deadlines.',
    'dr.faq.7.q': 'How do I get into this field as a student?',
    'dr.faq.7.a': 'Take electives in civil procedural law, take part in a pleading competition, do an internship at a firm with a dispute resolution practice, and apply to structured traineeships that offer a rotation in this field.',
    'dr.rel.label': 'Related',
    'dr.rel.title': 'Related legal paths',
    'dr.end.title': 'Start your journey in dispute resolution',
